# Introduction

The aim of this project is to create a system that utilizes multiple cameras to accurately determine the inertia frame location of an object. The objectives involve understanding the camera models, conducting essential calibration, and designing a triangulation algorithm that fuses information from the cameras. The focus of the project revolves around the development of MATLAB code to obtain camera data and efficiently process it using the implemented algorithm. The tasks required to complete this project are as follows:

- Get Familiar with the camera model.
- Perform Calibration in order to make use of camera info.
- Use MATLAB/python to receive data from Cameras and make use of it in the algorithm.
- Design a triangulation algorithm, that fuses the info from both cameras to determine the object’s inertia frame location.

# Camera Calibration

Camera Calibration is the process of estimating the parameters of a camera to accurately relate 3D world points to a 2D image plane. These parameters are split into two, extrinsic parameters and intrinsic parameters. The extrinsic parameters contain information about the position and orientation (POSE) of the camera with respect to the world coordinate frame. However, the internal parameters contain information that allows mapping between pixel coordinates and camera coordinates in the image frame, for example, focal length, optical centre and distortion coefficients\[3\].

The calibration process for the cameras involved utilizing MATLAB alongside its camera calibrator app\[4\]. It entailed capturing multiple images of a checkerboard and subsequently processing them through the camera calibrator app. As a result of this procedure, various parameters were obtained, among which only the intrinsic parameters were utilized for further analysis and applications. These parameters can then be loaded into the Matlab workspace as shown in Figure 4 below. The cameras’ intrinsic parameters, calibration images and other useful information about the camera can be found in the mechatronics.Group folder in teams.

**Note: The Extrinsic Parameters acquired through the camera calibrator application were not employed due to the existence of distinct transformation matrices for each image capture, stemming from variations in the camera's positional changes during the acquisition process. Consequently, a singular and consistent transformation matrix could not be applied universally across all the images.**

### Determination of Inertia Frame Location

The camera matrix for each camera was calculated by multiplying the intrinsic parameters (K-matrix) by the corresponding extrinsic parameters (transformation matrix) for both cameras.

Despite utilizing the camera matrix for both cameras, along with the pixel coordinates of a green blob, to ascertain its position on the flat surface depicted in Figure 12, the calculated location significantly deviated from the actual coordinates of the green blob on the flat surface, rendering the obtained result inaccurate.

The observed disparity between the calculated position of the blob and its actual location is attributed to a presumed erroneous estimation of the extrinsic parameters for both cameras.

# Next Steps

The successful completion of this project necessitates the execution of the following key steps:

- Identifying an improved methodology for the estimation of the extrinsic parameters.
- Utilizing the obtained extrinsic parameters to determine the spatial coordinates of an object in the inertia frame.
